04085nam a22005895i 9780804786348DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047863487 a10.1515/97808047863482doi  a(DE-B1597)564452  a(OCoLC)1198929398  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a323.4409731 aRedish, Martin H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Adversary First Amendment :bFree Expression and the Foundations of American Democracy /cMartin H. Redish. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction: The First Amendment and American Democracy -- t2. Adversary Democracy and American Political Theory -- t3. Cooperative Democracy and Public Discourse: The Flawed Free Speech Theories of Robert Post and Alexander Meiklejohn -- t4. Commercial Speech and the Twilight Zone of Viewpoint Discrimination -- t5. The Anticorruption Principle, Free Expression, and the Democratic Process -- t6. Adversary Democracy, Political Fraud, and the Dilemma of Anonymity -- t7. Conclusion: The Optimistic Skepticism of the Adversary First Amendment -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Adversary First Amendment presents a unique and controversial rethinking of modern American democratic theory and free speech. Most free speech scholars understand the First Amendment as a vehicle for or protection of democracy itself, relying upon cooperative or collectivist theories of democracy. Martin Redish reconsiders free speech in the context of adversary democracy, arguing that individuals should have the opportunity to affect the outcomes of collective decision-making according to their own values and interests. Adversary democracy recognizes the inevitability of conflict within a democratic society, as well as the need for regulation of that conflict to prevent the onset of tyranny. In doing so, it embraces pluralism, diversity, and the individual growth and development deriving from the promotion of individual interests. Drawing on previous free speech scholarship and case studies of controversial speech, Redish advances a theory of free expression grounded in democratic notions of self-promotion and controlled adversary conflict, making a strong case for its application across such areas as commercial speech, campaign spending, and anonymous speech.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 0aFreedom of expressionzUnited States. 4aadversary democracy. 4aconflict. 4aconstitutional rights. 4afirst amendment. 4afree expression and democracy theory. 4afree speech. 4aright to oppose. 4asupreme court. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804786348zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804786348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804786348.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles